I can't begin to comment on how (over)hyped this place is... Food: Ordered the beignet flight ($10), shrimp & grits ($13.75), and eggs benedict with pulled pork (special menu, $12?). This order for two people was actually a really bad idea since we had just came over from coffee and pastries at Sightglass. Definitely take your girl here :) Would definitely come back, but maybe, eventually, when the hype dies down... if ever. But cheers to this place!

Do you ever go somewhere and try to order everything on the menu?? - aka me at Brenda's. I came to brenda's with a party of 5 on Saturday. I was expecting a long wait but we were seated almost right away, it was probably around a 10 minute wait. They brought out our food sooo fast. Here is what I ordered: Gumbo: The gumbo was alright, I was expecting it to be a lot more flavorful. It had all the elements of gumbo but the soup could have been a lot better. The cup size is plenty for two people to share if you just want a taste and to order more things off the menu. Mac & Cheese: This side of mac and cheese is so cheesey. Again the side portion is shareable. Wasn't good or bad just standard mac and cheese. Crab Beignet: (Specials Menu) This beignet is SOOO GOOD. I don't know what I would do without it in my life. And the sauce it comes with is perfect. I'm not that big of a fan of the spices they put on top because I don't think it adds anything to the beignet itself but this is a must try. Crawfish Beignet: Very similar to the crab option. I believe this is on their menu all the time. I do prefer the crab one to the crawfish one because I feel like it had more flavor and texture to the food. BFC: omg this dish is huge! If you just want to try one piece of chicken go for the side order because it is still a huge portion. The skin was fried to a crisp and there was plenty of meat on the bones. Braised Pork Shoulder: (Specials Menu) This dish is severed with mashed potatoes string beans and covered in gravy. I think the pork shoulder was a little on the fatty side and overall the dish needed more gravy. Both of those were my own personal preferences but i still think this was very good. Seafood Pasta: (Specials Menu) This pasta had plenty of seafood in it, they were not stingy at all. I felt like this was a pretty basic dish, if you're craving a pasta this will do the trick!

In town for the holidays and was recommended this place by my friend and it lived up to the hype. Food was great. Decent location. Street parking, some residential if you are lucky. Good vibe. Had the flight of beignets: original, chocolate, apple, and crawfish. Also had the fried chicken with potato hash and biscuit. Mainly liked the original and crawfish out of the beignets. The rest were so so.. Depends on your taste but still decent. The fried chicken was very good and would definitely go back for round 2 if ya know what I mean. Service was alright.

Brenda's is the epitome of a professionally run restaurant, which is to say that they've maximized profit without alienating their customers. Their pricing is a gouge, but that's standard in SF these days. Their decor is minimally expensive, but smart. It's basically a warehouse space, but they've put down wood panel flooring, which is easy on the eyes, as well as the feet of their servers. The walls are concrete, but they've put up old mirrors on one wall (makes the space seem bigger) and on the other wall, they've commissioned a gorgeous mural. The overall effect is funky and fun. The chairs are wood with cushions. The tables are close together but not quite to the point of being suffocating. They use linen tablecloths, but glass tabletops. Smart! They've bothered to put together a music selection which is appropriate for the food they're serving. The food is not up to the level of the space, but it's not bad. The biscuits are some of the best in the city. Same for the grits. Their gumbo is quite good. Elsewhere, the cooks tend to have a leaden touch. Any sort of omelette will be cooked hard. Anything with cheese will have it slathered on. Fried breading will be heavy and greasy. (Their fried chicken is tragic.) Anything sweet will be sickeningly so. You get the idea. But still, most of the flavors and textures aren't bad, just lacking in finesse. You could do a lot worse in this city.

Thank you for taking over the space on Divisadero. Not only is it giving the space much needed revival but it also is making your lines shorter. I'm not one to get hyped up on brunch, I'm turned off by waiting in long lines for a meal that I can work wonders with, but this is one of a few stand out restaurants that I feel warrants a long line. For the record, I have never been to New Orleans, but regardless, Brenda's menu is satisfying and well executed. Don't come with too many dietary restrictions, soul food is not for the dieters. Come with a big and indulgent appetite. The cheese and shrimp grits are a standout for me as well as the poboy sandwiches. Go easy on their chicory coffee. A few cups will give you the caffein jitters. If you can make it in between the heavy rushes on a week day, a table is usually available right away. Hats off to this business for its consistency and charm

I've wanted to try the brunch food here for a while, but I never really wanted to deal with waiting in line for a table. So on a very lazy Sunday, I ordered from Postmates (they take Sunday orders from Brenda's after 2pm!). With that said, I can't speak about the service or the wait, but the food is AMAZING. Just be prepared for a pretty heavy meal, as is common with American soul food. Crawfish beignets: SO GOOD. And it was still freshly warm when it arrived! The pastry itself was a lot more dense than the classic beignets with powdered sugar that I've had at other places, but I didn't really mind. Filling was flavorful, had enough crawfish where I felt bad for whoever had to take them all out of the shells, and I loved the paprika on the outside. Hangtown Fry (fried oyster/bacon/scallion scramble) with grits: Didn't have AS much oyster that I would've liked, but nothing to complain about. I got more bites of the fried batter, but it actually tasted really great on their own. Grits were the best that I've had, but heavy because they were super buttery, so we ended up saving some for the next day. Shrimp & goat cheese omelette with biscuit: Omg I had no idea that shrimp could taste so amazing with goat cheese! Like everything else I had, this was very flavorful, and the shrimp were cooked perfectly. The biscuit was the best I've ever had also, and it tasted amazing with some butter and the housemade apple preserves it came with. So impressed with the food here!

Man, I'm glad i found this place and man, I'm glad it was on a Wednesday morning with ZERO line. Lucky! Walked right in and sat right down. Debated about the Shrimp and Grits but instead went for the beef fillets, grits and two eggs over easy. Yum! Coffee with chicory, New Orleanns style - awesome. Cool ambiance (you'll love the wall of mirrors, some of them are huge) and very creative menu. I can only speak for breakfast, but it was incredible. Fast service, friendly staff, and the owner walks around and greets everyone while they eat. It's these little things that add up to a lot - and that's what makes BFSF one of the top 10 breakfast joints in all of San Francisco. I'd avoid weekends, because the lines will be out the door (pop over to Cafecito instead, on Jones Street). Prices are reasonable - but mostly you won't get this kind of menu selection in many places - so go and enjoy!

    Do you ever go somewhere and try to order everything on the menu?? - aka me at Brenda's.

    I came to brenda's with a party of 5 on Saturday. I was expecting a long wait but we were seated almost right away, it was probably around a 10 minute wait.

    They brought out our food sooo fast. Here is what I ordered:

    Gumbo: The gumbo was alright, I was expecting it to be a lot more flavorful. It had all the elements of gumbo but the soup could have been a lot better. The cup size is plenty for two people to share if you just want a taste and to order more things off the menu.

    Mac & Cheese: This side of mac and cheese is so cheesey. Again the side portion is shareable. Wasn't good or bad just standard mac and cheese.

    Crab Beignet: (Specials Menu) This beignet is SOOO GOOD. I don't know what I would do without it in my life. And the sauce it comes with is perfect. I'm not that big of a fan of the spices they put on top because I don't think it adds anything to the beignet itself but this is a must try.

    Crawfish Beignet: Very similar to the crab option. I believe this is on their menu all the time. I do prefer the crab one to the crawfish one because I feel like it had more flavor and texture to the food.

    BFC: omg this dish is huge! If you just want to try one piece of chicken go for the side order because it is still a huge portion. The skin was fried to a crisp and there was plenty of meat on the bones.

    Braised Pork Shoulder: (Specials Menu) This dish is severed with mashed potatoes string beans and covered in gravy. I think the pork shoulder was a little on the fatty side and overall the dish needed more gravy. Both of those were my own personal preferences but i still think this was very good.

    Seafood Pasta: (Specials Menu) This pasta had plenty of seafood in it, they were not stingy at all. I felt like this was a pretty basic dish, if you're craving a pasta this will do the trick!

Filling was flavorful, had enough crawfish where I felt bad for whoever had to take them all out of the shells, and I loved the paprika on the outside.

    Hangtown Fry (fried oyster/bacon/scallion scramble) with grits: Didn't have AS much oyster that I would've liked, but nothing to complain about. I got more bites of the fried batter, but it actually tasted really great on their own. Grits were the best that I've had, but heavy because they were super buttery, so we ended up saving some for the next day.

    Shrimp & goat cheese omelette with biscuit: Omg I had no idea that shrimp could taste so amazing with goat cheese! Like everything else I had, this was very flavorful, and the shrimp were cooked perfectly. The biscuit was the best I've ever had also, and it tasted amazing with some butter and the housemade apple preserves it came with.

    So impressed with the food here!

    Man, I'm glad i found this place and man, I'm glad it was on a Wednesday morning with ZERO line.  Lucky!  Walked right in and sat right down.  Debated about the Shrimp and Grits but instead went for the beef fillets, grits and two eggs over easy.  Yum!  Coffee with chicory, New Orleanns style - awesome.  Cool ambiance (you'll love the wall of mirrors, some of them are huge) and very creative menu.  I can only speak for breakfast, but it was incredible.  Fast service, friendly staff, and the owner walks around and greets everyone while they eat.  It's these little things that add up to a lot - and that's what makes BFSF one of the top 10 breakfast joints in all of San Francisco.  I'd avoid weekends, because the lines will be out the door (pop over to Cafecito instead, on Jones Street).  Prices are reasonable - but mostly you won't get this kind of menu selection in many places - so go and enjoy!

    I was impressed with their chalkboard waiting list. As I expertly wrote my name on it for 3 people, I realized how big I was writing. For a minute, I felt like I was tagging.

    We waited a while, but not as crazy as I feared. Paired with a walk to Philz Coffee and good company, we did pretty well while waiting. No outside drinks, so my half-drank large cup of Philtered Soul was thrown out so we could be seated.

    I was set on fried chicken but sad to see they didn't have it on their brunch menu. I opted for the pork belly grits as my alternative. We also ordered the *beignet flight* so we could sample all the fillings. My favorite had to be the crawfish. It was coupled with cheese inside, so yay! The chocolate was good but the beignet itself was not as soft nor warm as I hoped it to be.

    My grits were delicious and the pork belly- so yumms. I ate around the tomato sauce they placed right in the middle of the dish, but good regardless.

    I'm definitely coming back for the fried chicken!!

    I was in the area and decided to check this place out. I have read such great reviews on Yelp about this restaurant but left feeling like I wasted my money on a mediocre meal. I came on a Saturday afternoon. My parents really liked the outdoor music they were playing outside. It had that jazzy vibe going on. The wait was about 30 minutes as I continuously checked the chalk wall inside the restaurant to see how many people were in front of us.

    Staff were friendly. It was obviously busy the time we came but our waitress took the time to explain the menu and what dishes she recommended.

    My parents and I ordered....
    Shrimp and grits $13.75
    Bowl of chicken, sausage, and okra gumbo $9.75
    Hangtown fry $13.50
    Crawfish beignets $10.50

    I read about how everyone was raving about the crawfish beignets so we chose this rather than the beignet flight which had a variety of plain, chocolate, Granny Smith apple, and crawfish beignets. (I think we made the wrong choice since the crawfish was just ehhh)

    Out of all the things we ordered, the only thing I liked were the shrimp and grits and the biscuit that the hangtown fry came with. Omg the homemade jam they have on the table is to die for. There was an option between peach or strawberry jams and we choose the peach. This jam on the biscuit was soooo good I could've just ate that by itself.  

    I probably won't come back again but it's always good to try new things :)
